[1] South Korea, 0 new cases, 1 new death - MOH 30 Jun 2015
Date: Tue 30 Jun 2015
Source: South Korean MOH 30 Jun 2015 [in Korean, trans. by interns at the JW LEE Center for Global Medicine, Seoul National University College of Medicine, Republic of Korea, edited]
http://www.mw.go.kr/front_new/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=323873


MERS-CoV Daily Update
- Total number of cases remains at 182: 54 currently receiving treatment (29.7 percent), 95 recovered (52.2 percent), and 33 dead (18.1 percent).

- No additional cases, 1 additional fatality case, 3 no longer undergoing treatment, and 2 additional recoveries compared to yesterday's data.

- Of the 54 receiving treatment, 41 in stable condition (75.9 percent), 13 reportedly unstable (24.1 percent)

- 82 have contracted the virus nosocomially, 64 have come in contact in-facility while visiting family, and 36 are of medical staff.

Overview of Confirmed Cases
- The Ministry of Health and Welfare's MERS-CoV Task Force has announced -as of 6AM KST, 30 Jun 2015 -that the number of total patients currently undergoing treatment has decreased by 3 since yesterday, bringing the total down to 54 (29.7 percent); in addition, 2 have made recoveries, bringing the total number of recoveries up to 95 (52.2 percent).

- There was an increase in fatality count by 1 to 33 (18.1 percent) and there have been no new confirmed cases for 2 days.
- Of those undergoing treatment, 41 are in stable condition while 13 are reportedly unstable.

New Recoveries
- A total of 2 patients have made recoveries on 30 Jun 2015, boosting the total to 95.

- The newly discharged patients are: patient no. 63 (68 year old female) and patient no.103 (66 year old male.

- Discharges underwent various courses of symptomatic treatments, such as antibiotic and anti-viral treatment. The patients were cleared for discharge after signs of respiratory distress and fever subsided, and confirmatory tests resulted negative.

- Of the 95 total recoveries, 51 (53.7 percent) are male with 44 (46.3 percent) being female; 25 (26.3 percent) are in their 40s, 22 (23.2 percent) are in their 50s, 16 (1681 percent) are in their 60s, 15 (15.8 percent) are in their 30s, 10 (10.5 percent) are in their 70s, 6 (6.3 percent) are in their 20s, and 1 (1.1 percent) in the teens.

New Cases
- No new confirmed cases

New Fatalities
- Patient no. 50 (55 year old female) was pronounced dead on 29 Jun 2015, bringing the fatality count up to 33.

- 33 reported fatalities consist of 22 (68.7 percent) male death cases, 11 (33.3 percent) female death cases; in terms of age distribution, the lion's share of the fatalities have been in the 60s and 70s with 10 (30.3 percent) fatalities each, followed by 7 (21.2 percent) in the 80s, 5 (15.2 percent) in the 50s, and 1 (3 percent) in the 40s.

- 30 of the 33 fatalities (90.9) were elderly, immunocompromised, and/or suffering from pre-existing conditions such as COPD, cancer, cerebrovascular disease, and diabetes.

Modes of Transmission and Demographic Characteristics
- There are no new confirmed cases. A categorical analysis on the modes of transmission is the same as that of yesterday (29 Jun 2015).

- Nosocomial infection is the most common mode of transmission (82 cases, 45.1 percent), infections as a result of hospital visits by family members comprise 35.2 percent of total cases (64), while infections of faculty and other medical personnel are reported to be 19 19.7 percent (36 cases).

- 111 (61 percent) of total cases comprise of male patients and 71 (39 percent) of total cases comprise of female patients.

- Total distribution by age of all cases is as follows: 41 patients (22.5 percent) are in the 50s, 36 (19.8 percent) are in their 60s, 30 are in their 70s (16.5 percent), 29 are in their 40s (15.9 percent), while 26 are in their 30s (14.3 percent).

Isolations and Quarantine
- As of 30 Jun 2015 6 AM KST, 2638 are under quarantine with the reflected numbers being 1.6 percent lower than previous day's numbers (a decrease of 44); the total number of those released from quarantine has increased to 13 354, which equates to an increase of 218 compared to previous day's numbers.

- Of the 2638 under quarantine, 2098 are under home isolation (a 5.6 percent decrease or a decrease of 125), while the number of hospital quarantines increased by 81 (a change of 17.6 percent), bringing the total number of hospital quarantines to 540.

