[3] Thailand ex Oman, patient recovered - media report
Date: Mon 29 Jun 2015
Source: Bangkok Post [edited]
http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/general/606364/omani-man-now-free-of-mers-virus


Omani man now free of MERS virus
-------------------------
The 75-year-old Omani man who was being treated at a hospital in Thailand after contracting Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) has been declared free of the deadly virus, the Public Health Ministry said on Sunday [28 Jun 2015].

Acting permanent secretary Surachet Satitramai said the latest test on the man found no sign of the virus and his condition had improved, although he still could not walk.

The Omani man is the only confirmed Mers case in Thailand and was treated for the infectious disease at the Bamrasnaradura Infectious Diseases Institute in Nonthaburi, where his condition was described as "satisfactory", according to Dr Surachet.

His condition has improved considerably, with better kidney function and increased lung capacity.

The man arrived on [15 Jun 2015] for treatment of his heart condition at Bumrungrad Hospital in Bangkok. His MERS-CoV infection was confirmed on [18 Jun 2015].

When asked if he would be allowed to move to a recovery room to continue receiving heart treatment, Dr Surachet said: "I have no idea about the man's treatment plan."

Prasert Thongcharoen, a virologist who serves as an adviser to the Disease Control Department, said doctors and health personnel from leading medical universities will meet today to discuss the man's condition and whether he can leave a special treatment room and move to a recovery room.

Three relatives of the Omani man and 156 others considered at high risk of contracting Mers who have been quarantined are in normal health, Dr Prasert said. They will continue to be monitored as part of a 14-day quarantine until Thursday [2 Jul 2015], he added.

